    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1909-08-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1909-08-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="39"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d39">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 21158.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Chargé of Austria-Hungary</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Austro-Hungarian Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Manchester, Mass.</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1909-08-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 18, 1909</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 2028.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Your Excellency</hi>: Rudolf Warren-Lippit, residing and
                    owning property at Thurnisch, Rann Parish, Steiermark, Austria, claims to be an
                    American citizen and is also in possession of a passport issued by the former
                    United States Legation at Vienna, No. 104, and dated December 31, 1879.</p>
                <p>The Austro-Hungarian ministry of foreign affairs has instructed me to ascertain
                    whether Mr. Rudolf Warren-Lippit, as well as his son of the same name, born in
                    1890 at Thurnisch, Steiermark, are really American citizens.</p>
                <p>I therefore have the honor to request your excellency to kindly have this
                    information procured, and permit myself to await an answer in due course.</p>
                <p>Please accept, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">L. Ambrózy.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
